SECTION 3 — RESTRICTIONS AND PROHIBITED USES

You MAY NOT use the Software, or any Derivative Work thereof, for any of the
following:

  (a) UNAUTHORIZED ACCESS — Using any feature of the Software (including but
      not limited to the SSH tarpit, canary files, fake twin login, or network
      decoy modules) against systems you do not own or do not have explicit
      written authorization to test or configure;

  (b) OFFENSIVE OPERATIONS — Adapting the Software's deception, monitoring, or
      interception features to conduct unauthorized surveillance, data
      exfiltration, man-in-the-middle attacks, or any other offensive security
      operation against third parties;

  (c) MALWARE DISTRIBUTION — Embedding the Software or any of its components
      into malware, ransomware, spyware, adware, or any software designed to
      harm, deceive, or defraud users without their knowledge;

  (d) ILLEGAL ACTIVITY — Using the Software in violation of any applicable
      local, national, or international law, including but not limited to the
      Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA), the EU Network and Information
      Security Directive, and equivalent legislation in other jurisdictions;

  (e) REMOVING WARNINGS — Stripping, suppressing, or obscuring the Alpha/Beta/
      Experimental stability warnings, disclaimers, or "run in a VM first"
      notices from the Software or any Derivative Work intended for distribution;

  (f) FALSE ATTRIBUTION — Claiming authorship or official endorsement of the
      original SecureForge project for Derivative Works without express written
      permission from the original authors.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SECTION 4 — AUTHORIZED SECURITY RESEARCH

The following activities are explicitly permitted without additional authorization,
provided they are conducted ethically and legally:

  (a) Penetration testing of systems you own or have written authorization
      to test, including use of the deception and monitoring modules;

  (b) Security research published in academic papers, conference proceedings,
      blog posts, or security advisories, with appropriate attribution to
      the Software;

  (c) CTF (Capture the Flag) competitions and security training labs where
      participants have implicitly or explicitly consented to adversarial testing;

  (d) Demonstrating the Software's capabilities to clients or stakeholders in
      the context of a legitimate security engagement on Authorized Systems;

  (e) Contributing improvements, bug reports, or new modules back to the
      SecureForge project.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SECTION 5 — ATTRIBUTION

All distributions of the Software or Derivative Works, whether in source or
binary form, must include:

  (a) A copy of this license in full;

  (b) The following attribution notice, visible in the software's documentation,
      help output, or about screen:

        "Based on SecureForge — https://github.com/yourusername/secureforge"

  (c) If the Derivative Work makes significant modifications, a clear notice
      distinguishing it from the original SecureForge project.

